of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Meriet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Merritt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Merritt","meanings":["English: variant of   Merriott  ,   Marriott  , or <b>Marritt</b>. The last of these is most often a variant of   Merriott   or   Marriott  , but possibly in some instances from Middle English <i>Marret</i> or <i>Merret</i>, a syncopated form of <i>Margaret</i>, <i>Mergeret</i>."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":14,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":27,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George de Meriet was born about 1301, in Chard, Somerset, England, his father, John de Meriet, was 26 and his mother, Ela de Beauchamp, was 13. He married Isabel Flory Fleury Kirketon Kirkton in 1325, in Merriott, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 5 November 1328, in Merriott, Somerset, England, at the age of 28."},"et":{"about 1301–5 November 1328":"umbes 1301–5. november 1328","1295–1370":"1295–1370","1297–1315":"1297–1315","1300–1370":"1300–1370","1301–1328":"1301–1328","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1322–1369":"1322–1369","1327–1363":"1327–1363","1276–1308":"1276–1308","1290–1381":"1290–1381","5 November 1328":"5. november 1328","1363":"1363","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1301":"1301","1322":